<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
    The <a href="/backlog/1352-webgraph-standard-shape-own-project-protocol-seam-count-a11y/">#1352</a> ruling
    settled the webgraph a11y <em>floor</em> — a tier-1 <strong>adjacency description-table</strong>, mirroring
    webcharts' <code>a11y-description-table</code> conformance case — but explicitly deferred the
    <strong>tier-2 model</strong> (richer traversal) to research, because <em>graph accessibility has no settled
    platform pattern</em>. A node-link diagram is neither a list nor a tree: it has cycles, multiple edges per
    node, and no single root, so the patterns that work for tabular and hierarchical data only partially
    transfer. This topic surveys the prior art so the eventual webgraph conformance a11y axis (slice D,
    <a href="/backlog/1376-webgraph-slice-d-conformance-cases-3-axes-benchmark-refs/">#1376</a>) can be specced
    on evidence rather than invented. <strong>It decides nothing</strong> — the tier-1 floor already stands.
</p>

<h2>Why the obvious patterns only half-fit</h2>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Candidate</th><th>What it gives</th><th>Where it breaks for graphs</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Adjacency description-table</strong> (tier-1 floor)</td>
            <td>A plain <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> / edge-list textual alternative derived from <code>GraphSpec</code>;
                works in every screen reader today, zero new pattern.</td>
            <td>Linear — it conveys the relations but not <em>locality</em> (you can't "walk" from a node to its
                neighbours), so it scales poorly past a few dozen edges.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>ARIA <code>treegrid</code> / <code>treeview</code></strong></td>
            <td>A keyboard-navigable, expand/collapse 2-D structure that screen readers announce well; the
                APG documents the interaction model.</td>
            <td>A tree has one parent per node; a graph has many. A DAG can be projected to a spanning tree
                (lossy: cross-edges become annotations), but a cyclic graph cannot without duplication.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>WAI-ARIA Graphics Module</strong> (<code>graphics-document</code> /
                <code>graphics-object</code> / <code>graphics-symbol</code>)</td>
            <td>Standard roles to label the SVG render's parts so AT treats the drawing as structured graphics,
                not one opaque image. A W3C Recommendation.</td>
            <td>Names roles but prescribes <em>no traversal</em> — it makes nodes/edges labellable, not
                <em>navigable</em>. Needs a keyboard model layered on top.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h2>The strongest prior art — structure-derived navigation</h2>
<p>
    The most promising line isn't a single role but <strong>generating a keyboard-navigable structure from the
    semantic spec</strong> — exactly what webgraph already has in <code>GraphSpec</code> (nodes + adjacency):
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Olli</strong> (UW Interactive Data Lab) — renders an accessible <em>structure</em> (an ARIA
        tree/treegrid) <em>alongside</em> a visualization, letting a screen-reader user navigate the data
        hierarchically with the keyboard. Directly applicable: a graph's adjacency can drive a navigable
        neighbour-by-neighbour structure rather than a flat table.</li>
    <li><strong>Data Navigator</strong> (Frank Elavsky et al.) — a toolkit-agnostic engine for
        <em>structure-based</em> keyboard navigation of any data graphic, modelling the viz as nodes + edges and
        moving focus along them. It is, almost literally, a graph-navigation a11y engine — the closest existing
        thing to what tier-2 needs.</li>
    <li><strong>Highcharts Accessibility module</strong> — the mature commercial reference: keyboard navigation
        across series/points, a screen-reader information region, and <strong>sonification</strong> (data as
        audio). Demonstrates the full stack a tier-2/tier-3 spec could mirror.</li>
    <li><strong>Mermaid</strong> — for declarative diagrams, sets <code>aria-roledescription</code> plus
        accessible title/description (<code>accTitle</code> / <code>accDescr</code>) on the SVG; a low-cost
        baseline that composes with the Graphics Module roles.</li>
    <li><strong>Cytoscape.js / sigma.js / force-graph</strong> — the dominant graph renderers ship
        <em>no</em> built-in a11y (canvas-based ones can't even be labelled); accessibility is left to the
        consumer. This is the gap the standard exists to close, and the reason the native-first default renders
        <strong>SVG</strong> (labellable) not canvas.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The rubric to score against</h2>
<p>
    <strong>Chartability</strong> (Frank Elavsky) is the established, testable a11y rubric for data
    visualization — a set of principles (keyboard operability, structure, text alternatives, visual contrast,
    etc.) that the webgraph conformance a11y axis should be scored against rather than re-deriving its own
    criteria. Pairing Chartability (the <em>what</em>) with Data Navigator / Olli (the <em>how</em>) gives the
    standard a grounded, non-invented tier-2 target.
</p>

<h2>Provisional tiering (to spec in slice D, #1376 — not decided here)</h2>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Tier 1 (settled floor):</strong> adjacency description-table + accessible name/description on the
        SVG render.</li>
    <li><strong>Tier 2 (this research grounds):</strong> WAI-ARIA Graphics roles on the SVG render + a
        structure-derived <strong>keyboard traversal</strong> model — focus a node, arrow to its neighbours,
        announce degree/edges — generated from <code>GraphSpec</code> adjacency (the Olli / Data Navigator
        pattern).</li>
    <li><strong>Tier 3 (additive):</strong> sonification and richer spatial cues (the Highcharts reference),
        never required for conformance.</li>
</ol>

